	Flynn in FBI interview denied discussing sanctions with Russian ambassador 

	By Sari Horwitz and Adam Entous February 16 at 4:37 PM

	Former National Security Adviser Michael Flynn denied to FBI agents in an interview last month that he had discussed U.S. sanctions against Russia with that country’s ambassador to the United States before President Trump took office, contradicting the contents of intercepted communications collected by intelligence agencies, current and former U.S. officials said.

	The Jan. 24 interview potentially puts Flynn in legal jeopardy, as lying to the FBI is a felony


Trump takes makes his widely anticipated/dreaded call with Putin, denying that he is being blackmailed. 
According to the Kremlin's readout of the call, Trump and Putin discussed "restoring beneficial trade and economic ties" and plans to organize a personal meeting between Trump and Putin in July. Pence was present for the call. The discussion of "economic ties" and plans for the meeting do not appear in the White House readout.

Meanwhile, Trump's travel ban is causing world-wide chaos. The ban caught the Justice Department and other U.S. officials by surprise, greatly adding to the confusion. Trump and his surrogates make public statements establishing the travel ban as religiously motivated, which is unconstitutional. Yates refuses to defend the ban, and Trump fires her for "betraying the Justice Department." Trump stresses that Yates is an Obama Administration appointee.

In the next few days, the White House is besieged by leaks showing, among other things, that Trump is incompetent and attempts to bully and threaten other leaders. The White House investigates the leaks, which Trump takes "very seriously." Trump blames the leaks on "Obama people." 

The leaks take-on new form on February 9th, when it is revealed that Flynn discussed the U.S. sanctions to deter election meddling with the Russian ambassador and made it unambiguous they would be revisited after Trump takes office. Meanwhile, Flynn is still vulnerable to blackmail, and Trump has not informed Pence that he was mislead. Flynn attempts to install an aide who's security clearance is denied by the CIA. Trump denies knowledge of reports that Flynn discussed sanctions.

It is around this time that Jeff Sessions is sworn in as Attorney General. Trump quietly signs an executive order changing the order of succession for the Attorney General, making Dana Boente next in line. Trump had previously picked Boente to replace acting AG Yates.

Trump keeps Flynn on for four more days. On the 13th, it is reported that Yates warned that White House Flynn was vulnerable to blackmail for lying to Pence. Trump fires Flynn a few hours later. Trump complains on twitter that the "real story" is the "illegal leaks coming out of Washington." Trump later charges that Flynn was brought down by "criminal leaks" from "intelligence." Wikileaks agrees.

The next day, Russia deploys a new nuclear missile, violating international law. Trump doesn't respond. House Republicans block Congress from obtaining Trump's tax returns.

In an oval office meeting that day, Trump singles out Comey to talk to him about Flynn and rant at him about leaks. Trump tells Comey Flynn "didn't do anything wrong" in talking to the Russians, but he had to fire him because he "misled the Vice President." Trump asks Comey "I hope you can see your way clear to letting this go, to letting Flynn go. He is a good guy. I hope you can let this go," although Comey doesn't make clear what exactly Trump wants Comey to "let go." Comey interprets it as Trump asking him to drop any investigation connected with Flynn's statements to the Russians.

Shortly after the meeting, it is reported that Trump's campaign was in repeated contact with Russian intelligence. Trump continues to publicly rant about leaks from the Intelligence Community and blame them on Obama-appointees. Trump claims the leaks will stop once he "gets his people in place," and his administration threatens to "review" U.S. intelligence agencies. Trump gives a press conference, threatening intelligence agencies, asserting he has nothing to do with Russia, and stressing that "Flynn did nothing wrong." A few hours later, the Washington post reports that Flynn lied to the FBI, and may by charged with a felony.


