The hunt for Donald Trump's tax returns continues. Grassley reveals that Comey is under scrutiny for the alleged FBI involvement with the "dirty dossier." Trump schedules a call with Putin.

Russian spy Julia Ioffe says the call is no big deal and "bleak" for Putin. During the call, Trump and Putin discuss Putin's "new ideas" for deeper cooperation in Syria and schedule a meeting for July. Putin asks Trump to meet Lavrov during his visit next week. Trump relies "yes."

Trump blasts Comey on twitter. At a hearing the next day, Comey struggles to find an excuse for his actions during the 2016 election. Spicer maintains that Trump has "confidence" in Comey, writing off Trump's tweets. Roger Stone gives a mysterious interview claiming communications with Trump and suggesting those communications were monitored.

Yates is scheduled to testify on her warnings about Flynn. Before the hearing, Trump points out on twitter that Obama also hired Flynn, and implies Yates is a leaker.

Trump downplays Yate's testimony, which reveals Yates believed Flynn was compromised and her warnings to the White House were urgent. Yates says that "if nothing was done" after the warnings it would be "concerning."

Clapper confirms that foreign allies passed the U.S. intelligence describing "suspicious contacts" between Trump advisors and Russian intelligence agents. Trump asserts that Clapper testified there is "no evidence" of collusion between Russia and Trump.

Yates testimony also reveals that Flynn was interviewed on White House grounds without a lawyer, that the White House knew Flynn had been interviewed by the FBI, that the White House asked DOJ about potential criminal proceedings and that the White House failed to notify the DOJ and other officials of Trump's travel ban, and strongly implies that the calls with the Russian ambassador were problematic and that Trump himself hid these from Pence, among other things (as previously mentioned).

The day of Yate's and Clapper's hearing, Rosenstein learns that Comey is to be fired. The next day, Rosenstein publishes a memo recommending Comey be fired for reasons that tend to criticize Comey for being too hard on Clinton. Trump had criticized Comey for going too easy on Clinton 6 days earlier. Trump cites the memo as the reason he fired Comey, saying he believes Rosenstein wrote it because of Comey's "poor performance before Congress." When asked later if he asked Rosenstein for a recommendation to fire Comey, Trump doesn't answer but says he was going to fire Comey anyway.

In Comey's termination letter, Trump stresses that Comey informed him "on three separate occasions" that he is not under investigation. Trump's lawyers assert there are no connections to Russia in the last 10 years of Trump's tax returns, except for some exceptions.

In an apparent attempt to intimidate him, Trump warns Comey that he "better hope that there are no 'tapes' of our conversations before he starts leaking to the press." Trump continues to rant about leakers, accusing Comey of being a leaker and charging that he had long ago asked Comey to "find the LEAKERS in the intelligence community."

The day after firing Comey, Trump meets with Russian ambassadors Kislyak and Lavrov in the Oval Office. Apparently, Trump hoped to make deals for closer cooperation and warmer relations between the United States and Russia and, reportedly, Trump told Lavrov firing Comey had relieved "great pressure." Trump described the meeting as "very, very good."

However, following the meeting, Trump is besieged by a series of dramatic leaks, alleging his incompetence and deep, sordid ties to Russia. Trump wonders "when does it end?" 

Trump posits that Comey will leak more than anybody could possibly imagine, in such a way as to be potentially "totally illegal" but definitely "very cowardly."


Trump told Comey he wanted his "loyalty," expressed his hopes that Comey could "see his way to letting Flynn go," asked Comey to "lift the cloud" of the Russia investigation over his dealmaking before firing him. For the question of "what was Trump's intent?" behind these actions, Comey and Trump give very different interpretations.





------


First, what they agree on: both agree the Jan 6th, Jan 27th, Feb 14th, March 30th, and April 11th conversations occurred. Both agree that that a lot of the press reports about Russian collusion get the facts wrong. Both agree that, at least at one point, Trump expressed that he wanted the Russia investigation to be done well. Both agree that Comey told Trump he was not under investigation at least three times, although Comey mentions telling Trump he's not under investigation on Jan 6 and Trump does not.

Besides Comey's view of his conversations with Trump, neither are aware of any other attempt to impede the investigation, and this is backed up by other statements and testimonies:


http://www.npr.org/2017/06/07/531897778/intelligence-leaders-testify-before-senate-panel-hearing
	DAN COATS: I have never been pressured. I have never felt pressure to intervene or interfere in any way with shaping intelligence in a political way or in relationship to an ongoing investigation.

	...BLUNT: And you would characterize your quote as no effort to impede the Russian investigation as still accurate?

	McCABE: That’s correct.

	...RUBIO: The question is, are you aware of any efforts by anyone in the White House or the executive branch looking for advice from other members of the intelligence community about how to potentially influence an investigation?.

	ROGERS: Are you talking about me? No.

	COATS: No.

	McCABE: I'm not sure I understand the question, but if you're asking whether we—I’m aware of requests to other people in the intelligence community, I am not.

	RUBIO: Seeking advice on how it could potentially influence someone, you're not aware of anyone ever saying or reporting that to you?

	McCABE: No, sir.


With Adam Entous being the odd man out:


https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/top-intelligence-official-told-associates-trump-asked-him-if-he-could-intervene-with-comey-to-get-fbi-to-back-off-flynn/2017/06/06/cc879f14-4ace-11e7-9669-250d0b15f83b_story.html
 	Top intelligence official told associates Trump asked him if he could intervene with Comey on FBI Russia probe 

	By Adam Entous June 6

	The nation’s top intelligence official told associates in March that President Trump asked him if he could intervene with then-FBI Director James B. Comey to get the bureau to back off its focus on former national security adviser Michael Flynn in its Russia probe, according to officials.

	On March 22, less than a week after being confirmed by the Senate, Director of National Intelligence Daniel Coats attended a briefing at the White House together with officials from several government agencies. As the briefing was wrapping up, Trump asked everyone to leave the room except for Coats and CIA Director Mike Pompeo.

	The president then started complaining about the FBI investigation and Comey’s handling of it, said officials familiar with the account Coats gave to associates. Two days earlier, Comey had confirmed in a congressional hearing that the bureau was probing whether Trump’s campaign coordinated with Russia during the 2016 race.

	After the encounter, Coats discussed the conversation with other officials and decided that intervening with Comey as Trump had suggested would be inappropriate, according to officials who spoke on condition of anonymity to discuss sensitive internal matters.


And Pompeo, as far as I can tell, so far remaining silent.


Amusingly, both agree that Comey is cowardly:


https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/873879934040780801
	I believe the James Comey leaks will be far more prevalent than anyone ever thought possible. Totally illegal? Very 'cowardly!'


http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/08/full-text-james-comey-trump-russia-testimony-239295
	FEINSTEIN: You told the president, I would see what we could do. What did you mean?

	COMEY: It was kind of a cowardly way of trying to avoid telling him, we're not going to do that. That I would see what we could do. It was a way of kind of getting off the phone, frankly

	...FEINSTEIN: Now, here's the question, you're big. You're strong. I know the oval office, and I know what happens to people when they walk in. There is a certain amount of intimidation. But why didn't you stop and say, Mr. President, this is wrong. I cannot discuss this with you.

	COMEY: It's a great question. Maybe if I were stronger, I would have. I was so stunned by the conversation that I just took in. The only thing I could think to say, because I was playing in my mind -- because I could remember every word he said -- I was playing in my mind, what should my response be? That's why I carefully chose the words. Look, I've seen the tweet about tapes. Lordy, I hope there are tapes. I remember saying, “I agree he is a good guy,” as a way of saying, I'm not agreeing with what you asked me to do. Again, maybe other people would be stronger in that circumstance. That's how Ed myself. I hope I'll never have another opportunity. Maybe if I did it again, I'd do it better. 

	...COMEY: ...I don't know. I think — as I said earlier, I think the circumstances were such that it was — I was a bit stunned and didn't have the presence of mind. I don't know. I don't want to make you sound like I'm captain courageous.


------

But neither of their stories completely hold up.

Trump says Rosenstein wrote his memo on Comey because of Comey's poor performance in Congressional hearings, and Trump describes his reason to fire Comey as "accepting the recommendation" of Rosenstein and Sessions. But Trump was planning to fire Comey before that, and Trump asked Rosenstein for the memo:


http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/read-rosensteins-full-opening-statement-comey-congress/
	On May 8, I learned that President Trump intended to remove Director Comey and sought my advice and input. Notwithstanding my personal affection for Director Comey, I thought it was appropriate to seek a new leader.

	I wrote a brief memorandum to the Attorney General summarizing my longstanding concerns about Director Comey’s public statements concerning the Secretary Clinton email investigation.

	I chose the issues to include in my memorandum. 

	...I sent my signed memorandum to the Attorney General after noon on Tuesday, May 9.


It looks like Trump was trying to hide his reasons for firing Comey.

Trump claims he "cherishes" the FBI, but it looks like Trump only likes the FBI when he thinks they're doing him favors:


https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/10/28/trump-says-fbi-letter-means-system-might-not-rigged-thought/WND8gcgRPAJDXd0EBerPaI/story.html
	October 28, 2016
	Trump says FBI letter means ‘system might not be as rigged as I thought’


