https://web.archive.org/web/20170124155639/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-director-james-comey-to-say-on-in-trump-administration/2017/01/24/033d3bc8-e246-11e6-a453-19ec4b3d09ba_story.html?utm_term=.13d7738addb2
 	FBI Director James Comey to stay on in Trump administration

	By Matt Zapotosky, Ellen Nakashima and Greg Miller January 24 at 10:21 AM 

	...The news that Comey would stay in place became public Tuesday, some time after he began informing senior FBI officials around the country that he had been asked to continue.

	Under normal circumstances, the revelation might have been unsurprising: Comey is less than four years into a 10-year term, and it is extremely rare for a president to remove an FBI director. But President Trump had notably declined to say whether he would keep the FBI director, telling “60 Minutes” in an interview after his election that he wanted to meet with Comey first. 


Assuming Trump is watching the media like a hawk as usual, Trump learns the following leading up to the dinner:


- Carol Lee, Devlin Barrett, and Shane Harris of The Wall Street Journal report on Jan 22 that multiple U.S. intelligence agencies are investigating Flynn's contacts with the Russian ambassador.

- Ellen Nakashima and Greg Miller of The Washington Post report on Jan 23 that the FBI found no wronging and Flynn is not under investigation.

- Matt Zapotosky, Ellen Nakashima, and Greg Miller of The Washington Post and Adam Goldman of the NY Times report on Jan 24 that Trump intends to keep Comey as FBI Director.


But Trump hasn't publicly confirmed he wants Comey as FBI director yet, and Comey has recently faced calls for his resignation. On top of that, Trump has reasons to believe the WSJ report that Flynn is under investigation is legitimate: for one, he probably directed Flynn's calls and knows their contents. And  Trump has said the Wall Street Journal and "financial media" are "much better, much more honest" than "the political media," and the Trump campaign had previously revoked The Washington Post's press credentials for "incredibly inaccurate coverage."

For a man who sees patterns and deals being made over the media (and perhaps fancies himself a mob boss), it wouldn't be too hard for Trump to interpret these Washington Post reports as an offer for a deal by Comey--essentially, keep me as FBI director and the investigation into you goes away. Trump would notice the conspicuous disconnected between the WaPo report and the WSJ report, and would certainly notice if the Washington Post learned that he accepted Comey as FBI director before he did. Trump might also have picked up that Flynn had been interviewed by the FBI within a few hours of Comey's January 24th "job offer."

Yates perhaps throws a wrench in this deal. Two days after the supposed Comey "offer," Yates warns Trump that Flynn is vulnerable to blackmail, then invites him to review the evidence underlying his conduct. But this would surely inconvenience any supposed deal to make Flynn's investigation "disappear," as the WaPo article enticed, as Trump would have a hard time pretending the investigation didn't exist with knowledge of both the investigation and the underlying evidence. Trump will later claim he was "surprised" by Yates warning, having "read various articles" that Flynn was "just doing his job."

Trump goes on to hastily create an alibi to fire Yates, his conspicuously unconstitutional travel ban, surprising Yates and everybody else with its roll-out and causing global chaos. Trump asks Comey if he's not under investigation then asks for his loyalty. Comey tells Trump he's not under investigation, and he'll get "honest loyalty." Comey keeps his job.





Trump will also claim he was "surprised" by Yates warnings about Flynn, as he "read various articles" saying Flynn "was just doing his job," indicating an awareness of the Jan 23 Washington Post report (the source for the "Flynn cleared of wrongdoing" story). Trump is also aware of the Jan 22 Wall Street Journal report--the WaPo report references it and the White House had commented on it. It is unclear if Trump was aware of the Jan 23rd CNN report independently corroborating the Jan 22 WSJ report.

Did Trump honestly believe the WaPo report over the WSJ report that Flynn "did nothing wrong?" It is hard to believe--Trump has said the Wall Street Journal and "financial media" are "much better, much more honest" than "the political media," and the Trump campaign had previously revoked The Washington Post's press credentials for "incredibly inaccurate coverage." On top of this, Flynn was interviewed by the FBI at the White House on the 24th  (and so adding FBI agents to the WH visitor logs) and on the 26th, Yates told the White House that Flynn was under investigation and the DOJ had evidence of misconduct.

After learning about FLynn's conduct, it looks like Trump was worried about a criminal investigation: on the 27th, McGahn came back to the DOJ with requests to see the underlying evidence and to discuss "the applicability of certain criminal statues" and "the likelihood that the Department of Justice would pursue a criminal case." In particular, it looks like Trump was worried about a criminal investigation of himself: 



at their Jan 26th meeting, Yates tells White House counsel Don McGahn that Flynn was interviewed by the FBI, and McGahn asks "how'd he do?" Yates doesn't answer, but McGahn comes back the afternoon of the 27th 




Trump will echo this claim that Flynn did nothing wrong, despite Yate's warning to the White House, Flynn being interviewed by the FBI on White House grounds , and the Wall Street Journal and other outlets reporting that Flynn is under investigation.




It's Trump truly believed the Washington Post report of the Wall Street Joural


It's interesting that Trump claims to believe the Washington Post over the Wall Street Journal--Actually,




