	HARRIS: Has anything you’ve learned in the months since your February 14th meeting changed your understanding of the president’s request? I guess it would be what he has said in public documents or public interviews?

	COMEY: Correct.







------

Several potentially relevant events lead up to the puzzling January 27th dinner between Trump and Comey:

- Trump has blamed the leak of the dossier on the IC, and appears to think U.S. intelligence agencies are leaking information on the Russia investigation out of hostility toward him.

- The Trump administration denied coordinating Flynn's contacts with the Russian ambassador and claimed they were innocuous, but the circumstances surrounding the calls hint at criminality or wrongdoing by Trump.

- Comey assured Trump he was not under investigation and refused to confirm the Russia investigation, and Trump has acted friendly toward Comey after others called for his resignation.

- According to Comey, Trump had asked Comey to stay on during the January 6th briefing, before the calls for Comey to resign. Comey also assured Trump he was not under investigation during this briefing, but this was before the "secret CIA assessment" and media reports on potential misconducted surrounding Flynn's contacts with the Russians.

- Meanwhile, Trump has been briefed that Wikileaks is affiliated with Russian intelligence, and Wikileaks has threatened to release Trump's tax returns.

In this context, Trump learns the following in the week leading up to the dinner:

- Carol Lee, Devlin Barrett, and Shane Harris of The Wall Street Journal report on Jan 22 that multiple U.S. intelligence agencies are investigating Flynn's contacts with the Russian ambassador.

- Ellen Nakashima and Greg Miller of The Washington Post report on Jan 23 that the FBI found no wronging and Flynn is not under investigation.

- Matt Zapotosky, Ellen Nakashima, and Greg Miller of The Washington Post and Adam Goldman of the NY Times report on Jan 24 that Trump intends to keep Comey as FBI Director.

Speaking later of the Jan 27th dinner, Trump tells Lester Holt that Comey had "wanted to have dinner because he wanted to stay on," contradicting these reports. But Comey later testified that he never asked Trump to meet for dinner.

Trump will also claim he was "surprised" by Yates warnings about Flynn, as he "read various articles" saying Flynn "was just doing his job," indicating an awareness of the Jan 23 Washington Post report (the source for the "Flynn cleared of wrongdoing" story). Trump is also aware of the Jan 22 Wall Street Journal report--the WaPo report references it and the White House had commented on it. It is unclear if Trump was aware of the Jan 23rd CNN report independently corroborating the Jan 22 WSJ report.

Did Trump honestly believe the WaPo report over the WSJ report that Flynn "did nothing wrong?" It is hard to believe--Trump has said the Wall Street Journal and "financial media" are "much better, much more honest" than "the political media," and the Trump campaign had previously revoked The Washington Post's press credentials for "incredibly inaccurate coverage." On top of this, Flynn was interviewed by the FBI at the White House on the 24th  (and so adding FBI agents to the WH visitor logs) and on the 26th, Yates told the White House that Flynn was under investigation and the DOJ had evidence of misconduct.

After learning about FLynn's conduct, it looks like Trump was worried about a criminal investigation: on the 27th, McGahn came back to the DOJ with requests to see the underlying evidence and to discuss "the applicability of certain criminal statues" and "the likelihood that the Department of Justice would pursue a criminal case." In particular, it looks like Trump was worried about a criminal investigation of himself: 



at their Jan 26th meeting, Yates tells White House counsel Don McGahn that Flynn was interviewed by the FBI, and McGahn asks "how'd he do?" Yates doesn't answer, but McGahn comes back the afternoon of the 27th 




Trump will echo this claim that Flynn did nothing wrong, despite Yate's warning to the White House, Flynn being interviewed by the FBI on White House grounds , and the Wall Street Journal and other outlets reporting that Flynn is under investigation.




It's Trump truly believed the Washington Post report of the Wall Street Joural


It's interesting that Trump claims to believe the Washington Post over the Wall Street Journal--Actually,
